  "passageText": "The advent and pervasive integration of social media platforms into daily life have undeniably reshaped the dynamics of human interaction. Initially lauded for their potential to bridge geographical distances and foster global connectivity, these platforms promised an era of unprecedented social cohesion. However, a deeper analysis reveals a more complex narrative, where the quantitative expansion of connections often comes at the expense of qualitative depth in interpersonal communication.\n\nOne of the most profound shifts observed is the gradual erosion of face-to-face interaction in favour of text-based or emoji-driven exchanges. While digital communication offers convenience and immediacy, it inherently strips away crucial non-verbal cues – such as tone of voice, body language, and facial expressions – which are fundamental components of human empathy and understanding. Misinterpretations become more prevalent, and the nuances of genuine human emotion are often lost in translation, leading to a superficiality that belies the apparent constant 'connection.'\n\nFurthermore, the curated nature of online identities and the omnipresent 'highlight reels' of others' lives have introduced new psychological pressures. Users are frequently exposed to idealised versions of reality, prompting upward social comparison and fostering feelings of inadequacy. This phenomenon, often termed 'Fear of Missing Out' (FOMO) or social anxiety, can paradoxically isolate individuals despite their hyper-connectivity. The constant pursuit of validation through likes and comments can also divert attention from authentic engagement to a performance-oriented presence, further diluting the quality of interaction.\n\nMoreover, the very architecture of social media platforms encourages brevity and rapid exchanges. Character limits, the demand for instant gratification, and the fleeting nature of online trends often prioritise concise, attention-grabbing content over thoughtful 